ndency, imperialism and the representation of disabled characters in popular fiction. These varied topics illustrate how common themes can be found in how Victorian philanthropists and administrators responded to those under their care. Often character, morality and the chance to be restored to productivity and usefulness overrode medical need and this both influenced and reflected wider societal views of impairment and inability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDisabilitieszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxPublic opinionxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Victorian Era (1837-1901).2bisacsh  aAlcoholism.  aBlind.  aCare.  aDeaf.  aDisability.  aEducation.  aExperience.  aHistory.  aPolicy.  aRehabilitation.1 aAtherton, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtherton, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCleall, Esme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFratz, Deborah M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHellal, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Iain, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLieffers, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorch, Marjorie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearson, Amy W. Farnbach, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSayer, Karen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVirdi, Jaipreet, econtributor.